      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 employed under ISO 9001-registered QMS. Software version control, regression test suite, and release qualification documentation are on file. Achieved level equals required level for this medium model risk application."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from NAFEMS and ASME V&V 10 suite reproduced within 1% of analytical solutions for linear elastic beam bending and contact problems representative of the screw-rod construct.",
      "rationale": "Three NAFEMS benchmark cases (LE1, LE10, and a Hertzian contact problem) were executed and results matched analytical reference values within 0.4–0.8%. Code verification is considered adequate for the linear-elastic dominated loading regime of this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation or systematic mesh refinement demonstrates discretization error below 5% for all three QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Four-level mesh refinement study conducted on the screw-rod assembly. Richardson extrapolation yielded discretization errors of 1.2%, 2.1%, and 1.8% for stiffness, yield force, and 40 mm force respectively. Production mesh selected at refinement level 3 where errors plateau below 2%. Achieved level exceeds required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson convergence residuals below 1e-4 force norm; energy residual below 1e-6 for all load steps.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analysis with frictional contact converged with force residuals consistently below 5e-5 and energy residuals below 8e-7 across all 11 construct simulations. No divergence or spurious contact chattering observed. Solver error adequately controlled."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation procedure with peer review; independent model build by second analyst confirms reproducibility of QoI predictions within 3%.",
      "rationale": "Simulation procedure documented in a controlled SOP. An independent analyst reproduced the model from the SOP alone; QoI predictions agreed within 1.4–2.7%. Use error risk is considered adequately mitigated at required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastoplastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening validated against Ti-6Al-4V coupon data; contact formulation captures screw-rod and screw-vertebra body interactions.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening model calibrated against Ti-6Al-4V tensile coupon data (R²=0.997). Augmented Lagrange frictional contact (μ=0.25) applied at all interfaces. Model form captures the dominant deformation mechanisms identified in preliminary sensitivity analysis. Achieved level equals required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties derived from lot-specific coupon testing; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of production hardware; uncertainty in inputs propagated via Monte Carlo (N=500).",
      "rationale": "Young's modulus (114±3 GPa), yield strength (880±15 MPa), and tangent modulus (4.2±0.3 GPa) sourced from lot-specific tensile testing of the same material batch as the F1717 constructs. Geometric tolerances from CMM data incorporated in Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation. Input uncertainty contribution to total QoI uncertainty quantified and documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs from production hardware; samples span manufacturing tolerance range; traceability to material certificates established.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs assembled from production-representative hardware with full material certificate traceability. CMM measurements confirmed all samples within drawing tolerances. Sample set spans the expected manufacturing variability range for screw diameter, rod diameter, and set-screw torque."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate ASTM F1717 protocol across at least two displacement rates and ambient temperature range 20–25°C; environmental controls documented.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min) per ASTM F1717 at ambient temperature (22±1°C). Only one test condition evaluated; rate sensitivity not characterized. Achieved level (2) falls below required level (3), representing a documented gap. This gap is noted in the decision record and accepted given the quasi-static nature of the loading and the limited rate dependence of titanium alloy at ambient temperature."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions, applied displacement, and fixture compliance replicate experimental setup; fixture stiffness measured and incorporated in model.",
      "rationale": "Test machine compliance (0.8 kN/mm) measured via load-cell displacement and incorporated as a series spring in the FEA boundary conditions. Applied displacement protocol, grip geometry, and UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate dimensions replicated in the model. Equivalency of input parameters is considered fully achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs; percent difference < 10%; agreement assessed at construct level not just mean.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed construct-by-construct for all three QoIs across both laboratories. Maximum E/uval observed was 1.78 (yield force, Lab 2, construct 7). Maximum percent difference was 7.3%. All 11 constructs passed both acceptance criteria for all three QoIs. Output comparison is fully achieved at required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements; linkage documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness relates to load-sharing with the vertebral column; yield force is the primary fatigue initiation predictor; force at 40 mm represents post-yield energy absorption relevant to catastrophic failure. All three QoIs are specified in the FDA guidance for spinal implant submissions. Relevance is fully documented in the COU description."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities use the same device design, loading mode, and material as the COU; any differences in geometry or material are bounded by sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Validation constructs are built from production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws — the exact device family addressed by the COU. Loading mode (ASTM F1717 compression-bending), material (Ti-6Al-4V ELI), and assembly procedure are identical to those in the intended submission context. The validation activities are directly relevant to the COU without extrapolation."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou1-noncannulated-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed required levels. The single shortfall — Test conditions achieving Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3 — is accepted on the basis that ASTM F1717 specifies a single quasi-static displacement rate and that rate sensitivity of Ti-6Al-4V at ambient temperature is negligible for the loading regime of interest. The central claim that the FEA ensemble accurately predicts compression-bending performance within pre-specified acceptance bounds is considered adequately substantiated. Overall credibility is assessed as sufficient to support regulatory submission for this medium model risk, medium consequence COU.",
